{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14792"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14792"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.19,0,0.05,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81817"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7483"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67094"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5153"},{"type":"tags","id":"7603"},{"type":"tags","id":"8412"},{"type":"tags","id":"9882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18310"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81817"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPhosphodiesterase-5 inhibitors are commonly prescribed medications for erectile dysfunction. These drugs work by interfering with a specific biochemical pathway in erectile tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents breakdown of cyclic guanosine monophosphate","Directly stimulates nitric oxide synthesis","Increases testosterone production","Blocks alpha-adrenergic receptors","Stimulates beta-adrenergic receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPhosphodiesterase-5 (PDE-5) inhibitors work by preventing the breakdown of cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP). During sexual stimulation, nitric oxide is released in erectile tissue, which stimulates the production of cGMP. By inhibiting PDE-5, these medications result in the accumulation of cGMP. This leads to smooth muscle relaxation in the blood vessels of the erectile tissue, promoting vasodilation and increased blood flow necessary for an erection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile nitric oxide plays a crucial role in this pathway, \u003Cstrong\u003EPDE-5 inhibitors do not directly stimulate nitric oxide production\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, PDE-5 inhibitors have no effect on \u003Cstrong\u003Etestosterone production\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Ealpha-adrenergic and beta-adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E influence vascular tone, they are not the primary targets of PDE-5 inhibitors and do not play a major role in their mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitors increase cyclic guanosine monophosphate levels by preventing its breakdown.","Increased cyclic guanosine monophosphate leads to smooth muscle relaxation and vasodilation in erectile tissue.","Nitric oxide is the initial stimulus for cyclic guanosine monophosphate production in erectile tissue."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67094"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14792"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67094"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T21:57:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T21:58:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7483"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81817"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30"